why_the_longevity_impact:
Why: The Longevity Impact
Total cholesterol provides an overview of cardiovascular risk, though individual components matter more. Very low or very high levels may indicate increased mortality risk.

Optimal Target
150-200 mg/dL. Focus more on HDL/LDL ratio and particle composition than total number alone.

Quick Tips
Eat more fiber, exercise regularly, limit saturated fats, include healthy fats like olive oil and nuts.

why_the_longevity_impact:
Why: The Longevity Impact
HDL removes cholesterol from arteries and has anti-inflammatory properties. Higher levels are protective against heart disease and associated with longevity.

Optimal Target
Male: 60-80 mg/dL, Female: 60-100 mg/dL. Higher levels provide additional cardiovascular protection.

Quick Tips
Exercise regularly, limit refined carbs, include healthy fats, maintain healthy weight, don't smoke.

why_the_longevity_impact:
Why: The Longevity Impact
LDL cholesterol carries cholesterol to arteries where it can form plaques. Lower levels are generally better for cardiovascular health and longevity.

Optimal Target
<70 mg/dL. Aggressive targets reduce cardiovascular events and support longevity, especially with family history.

Quick Tips
Reduce saturated fat, increase soluble fiber, exercise regularly, consider plant stanols/sterols.

why_the_longevity_impact:
Why: The Longevity Impact
High triglycerides indicate poor metabolic health and increased cardiovascular risk. They respond well to lifestyle changes.

Optimal Target
<80 mg/dL. Lower levels indicate excellent metabolic health and insulin sensitivity.

Quick Tips
Limit refined carbs and alcohol, increase omega-3s, exercise regularly, lose excess weight.

why_the_longevity_impact:
Why: The Longevity Impact
Lp(a) is a genetic risk factor for heart disease that's largely unchangeable. Knowing levels helps guide overall cardiovascular risk management.

Optimal Target
<30 mg/dL. High levels require aggressive management of other modifiable cardiovascular risk factors.

Quick Tips
Focus on other modifiable risk factors, maintain excellent diet and exercise, work closely with cardiologist if elevated.

Why: The Longevity Impact
ApoB measures the number of atherogenic particles and may be a better predictor of cardiovascular risk than traditional cholesterol measures.

Optimal Target
<80 mg/dL. Lower levels indicate fewer atherogenic particles and reduced cardiovascular risk.

Quick Tips
Focus on LDL reduction strategies, increase fiber intake, exercise regularly, maintain healthy weight.

why_the_longevity_impact:
Why: The Longevity Impact
Omega-3 index reflects cell membrane omega-3 content and correlates with cardiovascular and brain health outcomes.

Optimal Target
8-12%. Higher levels are associated with reduced sudden cardiac death and better cognitive function.

Quick Tips
Eat fatty fish 2-3x weekly, consider algae-based supplements, include walnuts and flax seeds.

RDW measures red blood cell size variation. Higher values may indicate inflammation, nutritional deficiencies, or increased mortality risk.

12-13.5%. Lower values within range indicate more uniform, healthy red blood cells.

Quick Tips
Ensure adequate B12, folate, and iron; address any underlying inflammation or nutritional deficiencies.

why_the_longevity_impact:
Why: The Longevity Impact
Elevated homocysteine is a cardiovascular risk factor and marker of B-vitamin status. Lower levels reduce disease risk.

Optimal Target
5-10 μmol/L. Lower levels reduce cardiovascular risk and support brain health.

Quick Tips
Adequate B6, B12, and folate; leafy greens, limit methionine-rich foods if elevated.

why_the_longevity_impact:
Why: The Longevity Impact
WBC count reflects immune system status. Both high and low counts can indicate health issues affecting longevity.

Optimal Target
4.0-7.0 × 10³/μL. Normal levels indicate healthy immune function without chronic activation.

Quick Tips
Support immune health with good nutrition, sleep, stress management, regular exercise.

HOMA-IR calculates insulin resistance. Lower values indicate better metabolic health and reduced disease risk.

Optimal Target
1.0-1.8. Lower values indicate excellent insulin sensitivity and metabolic function.

Quick Tips
Same strategies as fasting insulin: diet, exercise, weight management, meal timing.

Fasting glucose reflects baseline blood sugar control. Even within normal range, lower levels are associated with better outcomes.

Optimal Target
85-90 mg/dL. Tight glucose control reduces glycation damage and diabetes risk.

Quick Tips
Follow low-glycemic diet, exercise regularly, maintain healthy weight, time eating properly.

Why: The Longevity Impact
ALT is a liver enzyme that indicates liver health. Lower levels within normal range suggest better liver function.

Optimal Target
Male: 10-25 U/L, Female: 7-20 U/L. Lower levels indicate healthier liver function.

Quick Tips
Limit alcohol, maintain healthy weight, avoid processed foods, support liver with antioxidants.

why_the_longevity_impact:
Why: The Longevity Impact
Fasting insulin indicates insulin resistance. Lower levels suggest better metabolic health and reduced aging acceleration.

Optimal Target
2-6 μU/mL. Lower levels indicate better insulin sensitivity and metabolic health.

Quick Tips
Limit refined carbs, intermittent fasting, exercise regularly, lose excess weight.

why_the_longevity_impact:
Why: The Longevity Impact
Uric acid reflects purine metabolism. Both high and low levels may be associated with increased health risks.

Optimal Target
Male: 4.0-5.0 mg/dL, Female: 3.0-4.5 mg/dL. Optimal levels reduce gout risk and may support longevity.

Quick Tips
Limit purine-rich foods if high, stay hydrated, maintain healthy weight, moderate alcohol.

why_the_longevity_impact:
Why: The Longevity Impact
Vitamin D supports immune function, bone health, and may reduce cancer risk. Deficiency is associated with increased mortality.

Optimal Target
40-60 ng/mL. Higher levels within this range support optimal immune function and bone health.

Quick Tips
Get morning sunlight, eat fatty fish, consider D3 supplementation, test levels seasonally.

why_the_longevity_impact:
Why: The Longevity Impact
Ferritin stores iron and reflects body iron status. Both low and high levels can be problematic for health and longevity.

Optimal Target
50-100 ng/mL. Optimal levels support energy without increasing oxidative stress from excess iron.

Quick Tips
Balance iron-rich foods, donate blood if levels high, address deficiency causes if low.

This percentage shows how much iron is bound to transferrin. Low or high levels indicate iron disorders affecting health.

why_the_longevity_impact:
Why: The Longevity Impact
High-sensitivity CRP measures systemic inflammation, a key driver of aging and chronic disease. Lower levels indicate reduced disease risk.

Optimal Target
<0.3 mg/L. Very low levels indicate minimal systemic inflammation and lower cardiovascular risk.

Quick Tips
Anti-inflammatory diet, regular exercise, stress management, adequate sleep, maintain healthy weight.
